{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
The Tax Court upheld income tax deficiency determination, based on disallowance of taxpayer\rquote s depreciation deduction on transportation equipment used in the construction of taxpayer\rquote s own capital assets, and taxpayer appealed. The Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit reversed, 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1973109719&pubNum=350&originatingDoc=I235957fb9c1e11d9bdd1cfdd544ca3a4&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf5 \i0 
477 F.2d 688,
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb200 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 and certiorari was granted. The Supreme Court, Mr. Justice Blackmun, held that taxpayer was not entitled to current income tax deductions for depreciation on transportation equipment to the extent such equipment was used in the construction of taxpayer\rquote s own capital assets; that some weight was to be given to fact that regulatory agencies required the taxpayer to capitalize construction-related depreciation; that depreciation of construction equipment was an amount \u8216\'3fpaid out\u8217\'3f within provision of the Internal Revenue Code disallowing deduction for any amount paid out for new buildings or permanent improvements; and that priority-ordering directives of the Code required that the capitalization provision take precedence over the provision for depreciation deduction.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
